Description: This links to a video that looks into several example problems of evaluating different variable equations.

Description: This video talks about the newest gadgets that tracks and measures parts of your life, such as your diet and heart rate, and how these gadgets alter our sense of self.
This is a fascinating video about units and how 1 is defined in math.
Video title: One is One ... or is it?

Description: This is an interesting video that shows one man's impressive ability to multiply large numbers in his head!

Description: This video explains the rationale behind the definitions of zero and negative exponents.
An awesome video that zooms in and out of magnitudes, starting from an ordinary picnic.

Resource Name: How Folding Paper Can Get You to the Moon (3:49)
Description: This is an interesting video that illustrates the magnitude of exponential growth by looking at what happens when you keep folding a piece of paper.
Video title: How Folding Paper Can Get You to the Moon

Description: This video connects parabolas to the Mario video games. Learn how the jumping motions of Mario and Luigi go hand in hand with parabolas, their stretches/compressions, and translations.
This website lets you practice using order of operations to solve problems.
Play a game where you need to click the correct point.
Try to hit as many designated points as possible by graphing straight lines (using equations) in this game.
This game asks you to calculate the slope. With each correct answer, you have a chance to shoot a basket.
An awesome game that helps test your knowledge of absolute values.

Visit this site and calculate the probability of landing on each part.  Hit the record button and then click spin.  Repeat at least 20 times.  Did the actual outcome match your prediction? Why or why not?
This jeopardy game is a fun way to learn and review the different ways to solve systems of equations. You can play by yourself or with a friend.
This website allows students to explore graphs of linear systems by moving lines on the coordinate plane. When the line is moved, the equation changes.
This site allows you to remove a certain fraction of a line and see what fraction of the line is remaining. Through this, you can see a progressing geometric sequence that decreases exponentially!
Explore the relationship of between each of the variables in the quadratic function and how they affect the appearance of the graph in this simulation.
